@flexiarg ukrns/reader-as-participant
@title Reader as Diagnostic Participant (Meta-Pattern)
@keywords meta-pattern, reader-exercise, reader-participation, diagnostic-invitation, axis-visible, reader-consumer, reader-co-diagnostician, media-theory, pattern-reading
@audience UKRN-S design, working-paper authors, readers, funders, institutional leads
@tone analytic-foundational
@style meta-pattern
@references [ukrns/ARGUMENT ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing ukrns/measure-where-least-sure ukrns/open-the-triangle ukrns/computation-as-exploration]

! conclusion: A paper that states a tension, names two or three compositions, and refuses to rank them is addressing the reader as a participant in the decision, not a consumer of a conclusion.  The working paper's reader exercises are not decoration; they are the points at which the reader is explicitly invited to pick a position on an axis and justify it.  The paper teaches its reader how to read design patterns.  The service states which composition it is running on the axis between reader-as-consumer and reader-as-diagnostic-participant.
  + context: This meta-pattern is about the address of the working paper — whom it is written for and in what posture — and, by projection, about how UKRN-S could address its own network of institutions, trainers, and funders.  The five main patterns follow a Tension / Composition / Check structure that deliberately makes axes visible without prescribing a single answer.  The reader exercises (Reader — diagnose your current programme; Reader — which of these five would you commission first; Reader — what does this table let you say, and what does it explicitly not support?; Reader — if you had resources for Step 1 only, would you still progress?) are the places where the reader is invited into the diagnostic itself.  Take the exercises out and the axes revert to statements; the reader becomes a consumer again.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: reader-as-consumer (receives conclusions; reads for information) ↔ reader-as-diagnostic-participant (is invited to pick a position; reads for decision).
    Real: a consumer-oriented paper is faster to read, easier to cite, and respects the reader's time; a participant-oriented paper demands more of the reader and produces more friction.  Both orientations carry genuine costs.
    Irreducible: the same section cannot simultaneously deliver a closed conclusion and invite an open choice.  A reader confronted with 'you must decide which composition you would run' has a different reading experience than one shown 'the authors recommend composition X'.
    Active: the right orientation depends on the reader and the moment.  Early in a paper's lifecycle, when the argument is forming and the decision is genuinely open, participation is productive.  As claims harden and decisions are made, participation becomes performative (the reader is invited to agree with a choice already taken).  Audiences also differ: funders may want conclusions; institutional leads may need to participate; trainers may need to see themselves in the diagnosis.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Exercises at section boundaries: each section ends with a Reader exercise that asks the reader to pick a position on the section's axis; the answer is yours, the paper provides the framework.  This is the working paper's current approach.  Gives up reading speed; demands more of each reader.
    (2) Exercises consolidated at end: one 'working with this paper' section at the end collects all the diagnostic invitations; the body of the paper reads as a consumer paper; the exercises are a separate, opt-in layer.  Gives up the axis-by-axis participation; keeps the consumer reading path clean.
    (3) No exercises, maximum consumer-paced: the paper states the tensions and compositions but does not explicitly invite the reader to pick; the reader may infer the invitation or not.  Gives up the pedagogical move of teaching pattern-reading; keeps the paper's surface the shortest.
    These compositions are not ranked; the paper is at Composition (1) by deliberate choice and the exercises are load-bearing for the pedagogical claim (see BECAUSE).
  + BECAUSE:
    Pattern-reading is learned: The Tension / Composition / Check structure is not self-explanatory on first encounter.  A reader meeting it for the first time has to be shown, not told, that the compositions are genuinely unranked and that picking among them is the reader's work.  The exercises are the teaching moments.  Take them out and the Tension / Composition / Check structure reads as a presentation of options from which the authors have discreetly chosen one; put them in and the structure reads as a framework for shared decision.

    Unranked compositions require invitation: A paper that names three compositions and stops leaves the reader to guess the authors' preference.  A paper that names three and invites the reader to pick one makes the non-ranking explicit.  Without the invitation, the reader's default is to hunt for the authorial preference; with it, the reader's default is to consider their own position.  The invitation changes the reading posture.

    Refuses authoritative closure: The exercises are not merely participatory in form; they are epistemically humble in content.  'The answer is yours; the point is that the answer lets UKRN-S justify the next T1 budget on uncertainty-reduction grounds, not on general interest' explicitly refuses to tell the reader what to do.  This is the same epistemic stance as ukrns/computation-as-exploration (prior, not posterior) applied to the paper's rhetoric.

    Diagnostic reading teaches diagnostic acting: A funder or institutional lead who has read the paper participatorily has already done some of the work ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing asks UKRN-S to do.  The reading rehearsal transfers: having named a binding constraint on paper, they are readier to recognise one in practice.  This is the meta-pattern's projection into the main patterns.

    Projection into main patterns: UKRN-S's own address to its network could maintain the same posture.  Commissioned service documents, profile diagnoses, measurement-wave justifications could all invite the institution to pick a position rather than delivering a service recommendation.  The meta-pattern is thus not only about reading the paper; it is about addressing the network.

    Audience-shifting caveat: The right address depends on audience.  A funder's ingestion path may need more closure than a trainer's.  A paper (or service) that invites participation uniformly will be read as indecisive by some and respectful by others.  The service composes — per document, per audience — the right participation level.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: the paper (or service document) explicitly names axes, unranked compositions, and invites the reader to pick; exercises are load-bearing rather than decorative; the reader who skips the exercises has a legible but diminished reading.
    Failing when: the paper names tensions but quietly recommends one composition; exercises present but conclusory (their 'answers' are given by the paper); the reader is addressed uniformly as a consumer regardless of the decision being described; the participatory surface is ornamental rather than pedagogical.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - For each axis in the working paper, maintain a reader exercise that invites the reader to pick a position on that axis
    - Make the exercises genuinely open: the paper provides the framework for answering, not the answer
    - Distinguish axes where the authors do take a baseline position (e.g. ukrns/measure-where-least-sure favours VoI-first) from axes where they do not — the reader should know which is which
    - For UKRN-S operational documents: consider the same posture for service communications; where appropriate, invite the recipient to pick a position rather than delivering a recommendation
    - Audience-check each exercise: does this audience have the context to answer? if not, provide the context before the invitation
    - Track which exercises land: which are read, which are skipped, which produce discussion
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    For each axis in the working paper, the reader is explicitly invited to pick a position and justify it.  The exercises are load-bearing: the paper's structure teaches pattern-reading through them.  For UKRN-S operational documents, the composition on the reader-as-participant axis is a deliberate choice per document and per audience, not a default.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Conclusory exercises: the 'Reader — pick a position' is answered by the paper two sentences later
    - Decorative exercises: exercises present but unrelated to the pattern's axis; ornamental rather than pedagogical
    - Hidden recommendation: three compositions stated, one discreetly preferred by diction; the reader reads through the preference despite the non-ranking
    - Uniform consumer address: the paper addresses every reader as a consumer regardless of what is being decided; no participation invited
    - Uniform participant address: the paper demands participation from every reader including those who need closure (e.g. funders under decision pressure); produces frustration rather than engagement
    - Context-less invitation: 'Reader — pick a composition' without the context the reader would need to answer; invitation is formal rather than real
  + ANCESTORS:
    - UKRN WP draft-16-april (the Reader exercises throughout; the Tension / Composition / Check structure that they animate)
    - UKRN WP §1 Figure 1b 'Reading map' (another instance of the participatory posture — the reader is shown how the paper's layers map to decisions being put in their hands)
    - ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing (the main pattern this meta-pattern projects into: a paper that teaches participation is a paper whose readers can diagnose)
    - ukrns/computation-as-exploration (the shared epistemic stance: prior, not posterior; invitation, not recommendation)
    - Patterns literature (Alexander, Mehaffy) where pattern-reading is itself a skill the reader develops
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from the working paper's explicit reader-exercise scaffold and the Tension / Composition / Check structure those exercises animate.
    Meta-pattern character: describes the paper's address to its reader and, by projection, UKRN-S's address to its network.
    Projection into main patterns: participatory reading rehearses participatory decision-making; ukrns/diagnose-before-prescribing, ukrns/measure-where-least-sure, and ukrns/open-the-triangle all describe decisions that would benefit from institutional participation in the same posture the paper rehearses with its readers.
    Axis framing follows the same Tension / Composition / Check structure as the main patterns.  The self-referential character — a pattern about addressing the reader that uses the same pattern form to address its own reader — is deliberate.
    Coordination requirement: Low at paper time (single author team can choose the posture); Medium to High at service time (consistent participatory address across the network's communications requires coordination).
